Here none of our independent variable making any significant correlation with the tb per population which indicates that the rise in tb cases are not affected due to these variables.but we can see that the there are mutual dependency in few attributes. plot the tb cases across the 557 region of Brazil to see which region is affected the most in all three years.

Now as we have completed our data exploration part next we build a model and try to see is there any dependency in these cases based on other attributes.

library(mgcv)
## Loading required package: nlme
## This is mgcv 1.8-33. For overview type 'help("mgcv-package")'.
model1 <- gam(TBP~s(Poor_Sanitation) + s(Indigenous) + s(Illiteracy) + s(Density) + 
                s(Urbanisation)  + s(Unemployment) + s(Timeliness) + s(Poverty), 
              data = TBdata4, method = "REML")

Here also the R2(adjusted) is low in all cases,as we know The adjusted R-squared compares the explanatory power of regression models that contain different numbers of predictors.The adjusted R-squared increases only if the new term improves the model more than would be expected by chance.so we can say that none of these dependent attributes present in our dataset make any significance effect on the Tb/population due to which the dependency value is very low.
